# ============================================================================
# .dockerignore — trim build context for faster COPY + layer cache stability
# ============================================================================
# Why this matters for layer caching:
#   - Docker ships the entire build context to the daemon on every build. A
#     10 MB context is ~1 s transfer; a 500 MB context (with node_modules
#     or .git) is tens of seconds.
#   - Changes to files in the context invalidate the earliest COPY layer
#     that references them. Pruning noise here keeps the `npm ci` cache
#     warm across rebuilds.
# ============================================================================

# --- Never ship these into any image ---------------------------------------
node_modules
**/node_modules
.git
.gitleaksignore
gitleaks-*.json

# --- Local secrets (.env.* is only safe for the committed *.example files) -
.env
.env.*
!.env.example
!.env.docker
!.env.dev.example
!.env.prod.example
!.env.smoke.example

# --- Build artefacts that the image rebuilds itself, never inherit from host
dist
**/dist
build
**/build
coverage
.tsbuildinfo
**/*.tsbuildinfo

# --- Host-side SQLite persistence (smoke harness bind-mount target) --------
/data
src/data
**/*.sqlite
**/*.sqlite-shm
**/*.sqlite-wal
**/*.db
**/*.db-shm
**/*.db-wal

# --- Log output (never part of the image) ---------------------------------
*.log
logs

# --- Docs / ADR / tracking files (not loaded at runtime) -------------------
.context
docs

# --- IDE / local tooling / OS noise ----------------------------------------
.vscode
.idea
.cursor
.claude
.DS_Store
Thumbs.db

# --- Ephemeral helpers -----------------------------------------------------
.git-commit-msg.tmp
*.tmp

# --- Docker assets themselves shouldn't ship into images -------------------
Dockerfile*
docker-compose*.yml
